thread.title_full: Auburn's starting quarterback at Kentucky yet to be determined | AL.com

author: James Crepea | jcrepea@al.com
title: Auburn's starting quarterback at Kentucky yet to be determined
text:
It will be at least another day before Auburn names its starting quarterback against Kentucky.
After a tumultuous bye week, the Tigers (3-2, 0-2 SEC) head to Lexington for the first Thursday night game in Kentucky history with a decision between Jeremy Johnson and Sean White still to come.
Auburn offensive coordinator Rhett Lashlee was unsure when a decision will be made, deferring to Tigers coach Gus Malzahn.
"I don't know yet" Lashlee said following Sunday's practice. "Coach will make that call when it's time."
Lashlee would not say who took the initial reps with the first team on Sunday, as the open competition at quarterback , and across the depth chart, continues.
"Both guys are still competing, they did it last week, and they did it again (Sunday)," Lashlee said. "Had good urgency there."
Lashlee did continue to praise Johnson, who went 43 for 72 for 473 yards with five touchdowns and six interceptions during the first three games of the season before being replaced by White, for his improved confidence.
RELATED: Johnson still acting like Auburn's starting QB, says former coach
Last week, Malzahn said Johnson looked "more comfortable" in practice when he was in a backup role.
While being asked to do very little in the passing game during his two starts, White is 26 for 38 for 296 yards with an interception.
Auburn offensive coordinator Rhett Lashlee: Oct. 11, 2015 Auburn offensive coordinator Rhett Lashlee talks with the media after practice Sunday, Oct. 11, 2015, in Auburn, Ala. (Julie Bennett/jbennett@al.com)
Lashlee said the competition is "healthy" and believes both quarterbacks will benefit in the long run.
"I think it makes both of them better regardless of what we do," Lashlee said. "The best thing about those two guys, and I've been fortunate since I've been here – it was the same with Nick (Marshall) and Jeremy – they get along great. They're still good buddies."
Whoever the starter is this week will take the reins of an offense that's struggling to produce in many facets of the passing game. Auburn's 153.8 passing yards per game ranks 13th in the SEC and 113th in the FBS and a lack of deep passes is particularly troubling to Malzahn.
RELATED: Auburn hopes to build off most explosive performance of season
There is no plan for a two-quarterback system though. Whoever starts will likely play the whole game, barring injury or if the coaches decide to make an in-game switch they've been reluctant to make thus far.
"I think always the plan is to stick with the guy you start a game (with)," Lashlee said, "because hopefully that means you are doing well."
